\n<!-- Location ------------------>\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = {{flag|Morocco}}\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Regions of Morocco|Region]]\n|subdivision_name1      = [[La\u00e2youne-Sakia El Hamra]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Provinces of Morocco|Province]]\n|subdivision_name2      = [[Tarfaya Province]]\n|subdivision_type3      =\n|subdivision_name3      =\n|<!-- Politics ----------------->\n|government_footnotes   =\n|government_type        =\n|leader_title           =\n|leader_name            =\n|leader_title1          =  <!-- for places with, say, both a mayor and a city manager -->\n|leader_name1           =\n|established_title      =  <!-- Settled -->\n|established_date       =\n<!-- Area    --------------------->\n|area_magnitude         =\n|unit_pref                =Imperial <!--Enter: Imperial, if Imperial (metric) is desired-->\n|area_footnotes           =\n|area_total_km2           = <!-- ALL fields dealing with a measurements are subject to automatic unit conversion-->\n|area_land_km2            = <!--See table @ Template:Infobox Settlement for details on automatic unit conversion-->\n<!-- Population   ----------------------->\n|population_as_of               = 2014\n|population_footnotes           =\n|population_note                =\n|population_total               = 8,027\n|population_density_km2         =\n|population_density_sq_mi       =\n|population_metro               =\n|population_density_metro_km2   =\n|population_density_metro_sq_mi =\n|population_blank1_title        =Ethnicities\n|population_blank1              =\n|population_density_blank1_km2 =\n|population_density_blank1_sq_mi =\n<!-- General information  --------------->\n|timezone               = [[Western European Time|WET]]\n|utc_offset             =  +0\n|timezone_DST           = [[Western European Summer Time|WEST]]\n|utc_offset_DST         = +1\n|coordinates            = {{coord|27|56|22|N|12|55|34|W|region:MA|display=inline}}\n|elevation_footnotes    =  <!--for references: use <ref> </ref> tags-->\n|elevation_m            =\n|elevation_ft           =\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -------->\n|postal_code_type       =  <!-- enter ZIP code, Postcode, Post code, Postal code... -->\n|postal_code            = 70050\n|area_code              =\n|blank_name             =\n|blank_info             =\n|blank1_name            =\n|blank1_info            =\n|website                = http://tarfaya.info\n|footnotes              =\n}}\n[[File:Tarfaya 2016 01.jpg|alt=|thumb|The town of Tarfaya ]]\n[[File:Casa Mar Fortress in Tarfaya 2011.jpg|thumb|right|The fortress Casa del Mar, built by the British in the 1880s]]\n'''Tarfaya''' ({{lang-ar|\u0637\u0631\u0641\u0627\u064a\u0629}} - ''\u1e6carf\u0101ya''; {{lang-ber|\u2d5f\u2d30\u2d54\u2d3c\u2d30\u2d62\u2d30}}) is a coastal Moroccan town, located at the level of [[Cape Juby]], in southwestern [[Morocco]], on the [[Atlantic Ocean|Atlantic coast]]. It is located about 890&nbsp;km southwest of the capital [[Rabat]], and around 100&nbsp;km from [[Laayoune]] and [[Lanzarote]], in the far east of the [[Canary Islands]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://world-gazetteer.com/wg.php?x=&men=gpro&lng=en&des=wg&srt=npan&col=abcdeffghinoq&msz=1500&geo=-113471|title=World Gazetteer website|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120513045003/http://world-gazetteer.com/wg.php?x=&men=gpro&lng=en&des=wg&srt=npan&col=abcdeffghinoq&msz=1500&geo=-113471|archivedate=2012-05-13}}</ref>. During the colonial era, Tarfaya was a Spanish colony known as '''Villa Bens'''. It was unified with [[Morocco]] in 1958 after the [[Ifni War]], which started one year after the independence of other regions of Morocco<ref>http://www.sahara-online.net/Western-Sahara/Decolonisation-713.aspx</ref>.\n\nTarfaya is the capital and main town in the [[Tarfaya Province]], and counts a population of 8,027 inhabitants according to the 2014 census<ref>https://www.hcp.ma/downloads/RGPH-2014_t17441.html</ref>. Although founded in the twentieth century, the city has a big historical symbolic in the Moroccan history, dating back to the era of the [[Green March]] in November 1975<ref>https://www.historychannel.com.au/articles/moroccan-green-march-converges-in-tarfaya/</ref>.\n\nThe region of Tarfaya has been linked with relations with foreign powers, following several incursions conducted at its coasts (Spanish, Portuguese, British and French). This blending gave the city a special cultural dimension in its history. The famous French writer and aviator [[Antoine de Saint-Exup\u00e9ry]] (1900-1944) lived two years (1927-1928) in Tarfaya before writing his masterpiece [[The Little Prince]] that was later translated to more than 300 languages and dialects<ref>https://www.ctvnews.ca/entertainment/the-little-prince-becomes-world-s-most-translated-book-excluding-religious-works-1.3358885</ref><ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2005/04/03/arts/television/cover-story-a-prince-eternal.html?pagewanted=all</ref>. He served as station manager here during his career as an [[airmail]] pilot<ref>https://www.antoinedesaintexupery.com/personne/laeropostale-1927-1932/</ref>. In 2004, the [[Antoine de Saint-Exupery Museum]] was opened in Tarfaya.\n\nTarfaya is home to a number of economic projects, including the largest wind farm in Africa, called [[Tarfaya Wind Farm]]<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2016/nov/22/morocco-saharan-windfarms-tarfaya-fan-accusations-of-green-plunder</ref>, and the Casa Del Mar, named as the historical Victoria Harbor, that was founded by the Scottish trader and traveler Donald McKenzie in 1882<ref>http://sharinghistory.museumwnf.org/database_item.php?id=monument;AWE;ma;21;en</ref>. It is the meeting area of Atlantic coast with stretching sand dunes.\n\nSebkha Tah, the lowest altitude point in [[Morocco]] (55 meters below sea level<ref>{{Cite book | url=https://books.google.com/?id=EQqQBQAAQBAJ&pg=PT31&lpg=PT31&dq=tah+55+meters#v=onepage&q=tah%2055%20meters&f=false | title=Facts & Figures About the Middle East| isbn=9781633559448| last1=McCoy| first1=Lisa| date=2014-11-17}}</ref>) is located in Tarfaya province. Tarfaya is also the closest city to the [[Khenifiss National Park]], added to the [[UNESCO World Heritage]] Tentative list<ref>https://whc.unesco.org/en/tentativelists/1182/</ref>, an ecological site home to hundreds of different kinds of migratory birds each year. It is estimated that more than 20,000 birds from 211 different species breed, nest and feed regularly in the park<ref>http://www.eauxetforets.gov.ma/fr/text.aspx?id=1076&uid=87</ref>.\n\n== History ==\nTarfaya was occupied by the British in 1882, when they built a trading post called Casa del Mar.<ref>{{in lang|fr}}, acquiring their trading office.{{citation needed|date=February 2013}}\n [http://ecole.zzl.org/index.php/mon-pays/38-tarfaya/59-petite-histoire-de-tarfaya.html Petite histoire de Tarfaya] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402133851/http://ecole.zzl.org/index.php/mon-pays/38-tarfaya/59-petite-histoire-de-tarfaya.html |date=2012-04-02 }}</ref> The building is currently in a state of complete disrepair. The [[Sahrawi people|Sahrawi tribes]]{{which|date=February 2013}} then solicited the intervention of [[Sultan]] [[Hassan I]] who negotiated the withdrawal of the British in 1895 by Treaty of Cape Juby.<ref>{{cite book|last=Hertslet|first=E.|title=The Map of Africa by Treaty|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kGeM1IwCrBsC&pg=PA970|year=2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-01918-0|page=970}}</ref> In 1912 the territory of Tarfaya, then named [[Cape Juby]], was occupied by Spain as part of the [[Spanish Sahara]]. The greater Cape Juby region plus Tarfaya were unified with Morocco in 1958, at the end of the [[Ifni War]]. In December 2014 the [[Tarfaya Wind Farm]], largest wind farm in Africa, was commissioned.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.utilities-me.com/article-3227-gdf-suez-launches-560mn-morrocan-wind-farm/|title=GDF SUEZ launches $560mn Moroccan wind farm - utilities-me.com|first=Utilities ME|last=Staff|website=www.utilities-me.com}}</ref>\n\n== A\u00e9ropostale ==\nTarfaya's association with [[A\u00e9ropostale (aviation)|A\u00e9ropostale]] began in 1927. The airmail carrier, based in [[Toulouse, France]], was founded by French industrialist [[Pierre-Georges Lat\u00e9co\u00e8re]], who envisioned an air route connecting France to its French colonies in Africa. Lat\u00e9co\u00e8re firmly believed in the future of aviation as a means of commercial transportation and communication between people.\n\nThe nearby Cape Juby airfield was an important refueling and stopover station for A\u00e9ropostale. Author-aviator [[Antoine de Saint-Exup\u00e9ry]] was named its station manager in 1927. There he remained for 18 months, on occasion negotiating with the rebellious [[Moors|Moorish tribes]] to release his imprisoned pilots, as he wrote in his first novel, ''Southern Mail''.\n\nOn 28 September 2004 a museum opened in honour of the memory of A\u00e9ropostale, Saint-Exup\u00e9ry and its pilots, supported notably by the city of Toulouse and European aircraft maker [[Airbus]]. The museum was inaugurated by renowned aviation journalist Bernard Chabbert, whose father was also part of A\u00e9ropostale's history.\n[[File:Antoine de Saint Exup\u00e9ry Museum Interior View Panorama Aug 2017.jpg|center|thumb|980x980px|'''Saint Exup\u00e9ry Museum in Tarfaya opened in honour of the memory of A\u00e9ropostale''']]\n\n== Air services ==\n\nThe town maintains the [[Tarfaya Airport]] with the [[IATA]] code TFY.[[File:Tarfaya Saint-Exupery.jpg|thumb|right|Monument dedicated to [[Antoine de Saint-Exup\u00e9ry|Antoine de Saint Exup\u00e9ry]], the author and the airport manager of [[A\u00e9ropostale (aviation)|L'A\u00e9ropostale]] at Cap Juby, just by Tarfaya]]\n== Climate ==\nTarfaya has a [[desert climate]] (BWh/BWk).\n{{Weather box\n|location = Tarfaya\n|metric first = yes\n|single line = yes\n|Jan high C = 19\n|Feb high C = 19\n|Mar high C = 20\n|Apr high C = 21\n|May high C = 21\n|Jun high C = 22\n|Jul high C = 22\n|Aug high C = 23\n|Sep high C = 23\n|Oct high C = 23\n|Nov high C = 22\n|Dec high C = 20\n|year high C = 21\n|Jan mean C = 16\n|Feb mean C = 16\n|Mar mean C = 17\n|Apr mean C = 18\n|May mean C = 18\n|Jun mean C = 19\n|Jul mean C = 20\n|Aug mean C = 20\n|Sep mean C = 20\n|Oct mean C = 20\n|Nov mean C = 19\n|Dec mean C = 16\n|year mean C = 18\n|Jan low C = 13\n|Feb low C = 13\n|Mar low C = 14\n|Apr low C = 15\n|May low C = 16\n|Jun low C = 17\n|Jul low C = 18\n|Aug low C = 18\n|Sep low C = 18\n|Oct low C = 17\n|Nov low C = 16\n|Dec low C = 13\n|year low C = 16\n|Jan precipitation cm = 0\n|Feb precipitation cm = 0\n|Mar precipitation cm = 0\n|Apr precipitation cm = 0\n|May precipitation cm = 0\n|Jun precipitation cm = 0\n|Jul precipitation cm = 0\n|Aug precipitation cm = 0\n|Sep precipitation cm = 0\n|Oct precipitation cm = 0\n|Nov precipitation cm = 1\n|Dec precipitation cm = 0\n|year precipitation cm = 1\n|source 1 = Weatherbase<ref name=\"Weatherbase\">{{cite web\n  |url=http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weatherall.php3?s=196006&refer=&units=metric\n  |title=Weatherbase: Historical Weather for Tarfaya\n  |accessdate=}}</ref>\n|date=August 2010\n}}\n\n== References ==\n{{commons category}}\n\n;Citations\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n;Bibliography\n\n* Didier Daurat, [https://books.google.com/books?id=JAIYHQAACAAJ ''Saint-Exup\u00e9ry tel que je l'ai connu''], France: \u00c9dition Dynamo, 1954.\n\n{{Coord|27|56|22|N|12|55|34|W|region:MA_type:city|display=title}}\n{{Laayoune-Sakia El Hamra}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in La\u00e2youne-Sakia El Hamra]]\n[[Category:1882 establishments in the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Provincial capitals in Morocco|Tarfaya]]\n[[Category:Tarfaya]]\n", "name_user": "Rossh1", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eA\u00e9ropostale:Added wikilink to Antoine de Saint-Exupery Museum page", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tarfaya"}
{"title_page": "Saint Martin de Porres (sculpture)", "text_new": "{{Infobox artwork\n| image_file = \n| painting_alignment = \n| image_size         = \n| title              = Saint Martin de Porres\n| alt                = \n| other_language_1   = \n| other_title_1      = \n| other_language_2   =\n| other_title_2      = \n| artist             = Fr. Thomas McGlynn\n| year               = 1963\n| height_metric      =\n| width_metric       = \n| length_metric      = \n| height_imperial    = \n| width_imperial     = \n| length_imperial    = \n| diameter_metric    = \n| diameter_imperial  =\n| metric_unit        = cm\n| imperial_unit      = in \n| city               = \n| museum             = \n| coordinates        = \n| owner              = \n}}\n\n'''''Saint Martin de Porres''''' is an artwork by [[United States|American]] artist and [[Catholic priest]] [[Thomas McGlynn|Father Thomas McGlynn]]. This sculpture, one of McGlynn's most well known works, is found in the collection of [[Providence College]] in [[Rhode Island]], [[Old Lady of Perpetual Help Church (Washington, D.C.)|Our Lady of Perpetual Help Church]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], among others. It is a statue of Saint [[Martin de Porres]].<ref name=\"SOS1993\">{{cite web | author=Smithsonian | year=1993 | title=St. Martin Fountain, (sculpture). | work=Save Outdoor Sculpture | publisher=Smithsonian | url=http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?&profile=all&source=~!siartinventories&uri=full=3100001~!319554~!0#focus | accessdate= 12 January 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"SOS1994\">{{cite web | author=Smithsonian | year=1994 | title=Saint Martin de Porres, (sculpture). | work=Save Outdoor Sculpture | publisher=Smithsonian | url=http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?&profile=all&source=~!siartinventories&uri=full=3100001~!323793~!0#focus | accessdate= 12 January 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\n\nThe sculpture is a standing figure of Saint Martin de Porres wearing a [[cassock]] with a belt at the waist, he wears shoes. His head looks downwards, eyes somewhat closed, as if in deep thought or prayer. In his proper right hand he holds a [[Christian cross|cross]] to his chest and his proper left hand grips his leg with a broom under his arm.<ref name=\"SOS1994\"/> Some of the works of this piece feature the Saint looking down at [[rat]]s that have gathered at his feet, often featuring 2\u20133 rats.<ref name=\"MartinHallSOS\"/>\n\n==Father Thomas McGlynn==\n\nMcGlynn was born May 23, 1906 to [[Frank McGlynn, Sr.|Frank McGlynn]] and Rose O'Beirne. On September 8, 1925 he received the habit of the [[Dominican Order]], taking the name Brother Matthew. At Dominic's Church in Washington, D.C., he was [[ordained]] a priest on May 20, 1932 by [[Michael Joseph Curley|Archbishop Michael Joseph Curley]]. Receiving his degree in sculpture in [[Rome, Italy]] in 1934 and returned to the United States to study at [[Cranbrook Educational Community]] studying under [[Carl Milles]]. After apostolic ministry and serving as faculty member at Providence College (1937\u20131938 and 1946), he went to [[Pietrasanta, Italy]] in 1956 commissioned to create a sculpture of [[Our Lady of Fatima]] and he remained in the country until his death on September 3, 1977.<ref name=\"MartinHallSOS\">{{cite web | author=Smithsonian | year=1993 | title=Saint Martin de Porres, (sculpture). | work=Save Outdoor Sculpture | publisher=Smithsonian | url=http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?&profile=all&source=~!siartinventories&uri=full=3100001~!319555~!0#focus | accessdate= 12 January 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"McGlynn\">{{cite web | author=Fr. Richard McAlister OP | title=Dominican Priest and Sculptor Thomas McGlynn | work=Theology | publisher=Providence College | url=http://www.domcentral.org/library/McGlynn/default.htm | accessdate=12 January 2010 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100501091551/http://www.domcentral.org/library/McGlynn/default.htm | archivedate=1 May 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==Inspiration and Creation==\n\nGrowing up, McGlynn was unaware of racial issues during his youth, using discriminatory terms as part of everyday life to describe [[African Americans]]. Upon entering the priesthood McGlynn states that \"My meeting with Martin de Porres changed all that.\"<ref name=\"Homily\">{{cite web | author=Fr. Pius Pietrzyk, O.P. | year=2010 | title=Fr. Thomas McGlynn and St. Martin de Porres | work=Friar Blog | publisher=The Dominican Province of Saint Joseph | url=http://www.op-stjoseph.org/blog/fr._thomas_mcglynn_and_st._martin_de_porres/ | accessdate= 12 January 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Locations==\nFour versions of the sculpture exist, and the creation of this work is often credited with contributing to the [[canonization]] of the Saint in 1962.<ref name=\"2009McGlynn\">{{cite web | year=2009 | title=Selected Works of Thomas McGlynn | work=Thomas McGlynn | publisher=Providence College | url=http://www.domcentral.org/library/McGlynn/mcg09.htm | accessdate=12 January 2010 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101229191514/http://www.domcentral.org/library/McGlynn/mcg09.htm | archivedate=29 December 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==Dominican House of Studies==\n\nThe original [[plaster]] version of the sculpture resided in the collection of the Dominican House of Studies in Washington, D.C. as of 1962.<ref name=\"2009McGlynn\"/>\n\n===Vatican===\n\nThe first, small version of the sculpture was created for use at the Vatican, completed in 1962.<ref name=\"2009McGlynn\"/>\n\n===Providence College===\n\nProvidence College has two copies of the sculpture, one in front of Martin Hall and a second at the McGlynn Sculpture Court, named after the sculptor. The Martin Hall sculpture, the fourth in the series, has no rats at the Saints feet, is made of [[bronze]] (H. 7&nbsp;ft.) and was copyrighted in 1958 and dedicated on November 3, 1979.<ref name=\"MartinHallSOS\"/> This version was originally designed for [[Saint Raymond's Cemetery, Bronx|Saint Raymond's Cemetery]] in the Bronx, New York City, and McGlynn decided to remove the rats believing that people would have an aversion to them being on a sculpture in a cemetery.<ref name=\"2009McGlynn\"/> It was surveyed in 1993 by the [[Smithsonian Institution|Smithsonian's]] [[Save Outdoor Sculpture!]] program and was described as needing treatment.<ref name=\"MartinHallSOS\"/>  \n\nThe second sculpture, at McGlynn Sculpture Court, features several small rats at the Saints feet. This is an earlier version of the above piece, made also of bronze (H. 48 in. \u00d7 W. 1&nbsp;ft. 3 in.), created in 1962, cast in 1963 and dedicated on October 2, 1993. The sculpture stands in a small fountain. as part of the Sculpture Court which was built after the [[Dominican Province of St. Joseph]] donated their McGlynn Archives & Sculpture Collection to the College in 1980. This sculpture was described as well maintained by the Save Outdoor Sculpture! survey program.<ref name=\"SOS1993\"/>\n\n==Our Lady of Perpetual Help Church==\n\nThis version of the sculpture is made of [[wood]] (H. 12{{frac|1|2}} ft.) and does not feature the rats at his feet. It was dedicated on May 27, 1989 with the support of the St. Martin de Porres Guild and the founding pastor who wanted the church to be dedicated in the Saints honor. The funds for the work were provided by an endowment supplied by parishioner Mary A. Cooke, who hoped to have the statue erected inside the church school. The piece resides outside. The work was described as needing treatment in 1994 by the Save Outdoor Sculpture! survey program.<ref name=\"SOS1994\"/>\n\n===Roman Catholic Diocese of Raleigh===\n\nOn November 3, 2009, the parish of St. Joseph in [[Raleigh, North Carolina]] was presented a four-foot-tall version of the sculpture by Fr. Ambrose McAlister, Professor Emeritus of Art and Art History at Providence College, to celebrate the Feast of St. Martin de Porres.<ref name=\"Homily\"/> This black marble casting was made from the 1930 version and was created in a Rhode Island-based foundry. It sits upon a table of white [[carrara marble]], which was crafted by parish member Bill Stephany. Fundraising for the work and installation was spearheaded by parish member Daisy Foster. Father McGlynn worked in Raleigh at St. Monica's from 1947 to 1954.<ref name=\"Raleigh\">{{cite web | author=St. Martin de Porres | year= | title=St. Martin de Porres | work= | publisher=St. Joseph's Catholic Church | url=http://stjosephsraleigh.org/index.php?option=com_content&id=92 | accessdate= 12 January 2010}}</ref>\n\n===St. Martin de Porres Shrine & Institute, Memphis, Tennessee===\n\nThe shrine chapel features a small version of the 1930 casting which shares the space with a [[relic]] of St. Martin as well as a stained-glass window and icons created by [[Pam Hassler]].<ref name=\"Shrine\">{{cite web | year=2010 | title=Shrine Artwork | work=The Shrine Chapel | publisher=St. Martin de Porres Shrine & Institute | url=http://www.stmartinshrine.org/shrinechapel.html | accessdate=12 January 2010 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100826074913/http://www.stmartinshrine.org/shrinechapel.html | archivedate=26 August 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20101229190116/http://www.domcentral.org/library/McGlynn/mcg03.htm Learn more about Father McGlynn]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Public art in Washington, D.C.}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saint Martin De Porres (Sculpture)}}\n[[Category:Providence College]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials in Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:Culture of Providence, Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Outdoor sculptures in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Sculptures of saints]]\n[[Category:Woodcarving]]\n[[Category:Catholic Church in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:African-American Roman Catholicism]]\n[[Category:1963 sculptures]]\n[[Category:Bronze sculptures in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artwork\n| image_file = \n| painting_alignment = \n| image_size         = \n| title              = Saint Martin de Porres\n| alt                = \n| other_language_1   = \n| other_title_1      = \n| other_language_2   =\n| other_title_2      = \n| artist             = Fr. Thomas McGlynn\n| year               = 1963\n| height_metric      =\n| width_metric       = \n| length_metric      = \n| height_imperial    = \n| width_imperial     = \n| length_imperial    = \n| diameter_metric    = \n| diameter_imperial  =\n| metric_unit        = cm\n| imperial_unit      = in \n| city               = \n| museum             = \n| coordinates        = \n| owner              = \n}}\n\n'''''Saint Martin de Porres''''' is an artwork by [[United States|American]] artist and [[Catholic priest]] [[Thomas McGlynn|Father Thomas McGlynn]]. This sculpture, one of McGlynn's most well known works, is found in the collection of [[Providence College]] in [[Rhode Island]], [[Old Lady of Perpetual Help Church (Washington, D.C.)|Our Lady of Perpetual Help Church]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], among others. It is a statue of Saint [[Martin de Porres]].<ref name=\"SOS1993\">{{cite web | author=Smithsonian | year=1993 | title=St. Martin Fountain, (sculpture). | work=Save Outdoor Sculpture | publisher=Smithsonian | url=http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?&profile=all&source=~!siartinventories&uri=full=3100001~!319554~!0#focus | accessdate= 12 January 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"SOS1994\">{{cite web | author=Smithsonian | year=1994 | title=Saint Martin de Porres, (sculpture). | work=Save Outdoor Sculpture | publisher=Smithsonian | url=http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?&profile=all&source=~!siartinventories&uri=full=3100001~!323793~!0#focus | accessdate= 12 January 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\n\nThe sculpture is a standing figure of Saint Martin de Porres wearing a [[cassock]] with a belt at the waist, he wears shoes. His head looks downwards, eyes somewhat closed, as if in deep thought or prayer. In his proper right hand he holds a [[Christian cross|cross]] to his chest and his proper left hand grips his leg with a broom under his arm.<ref name=\"SOS1994\"/> Some of the works of this piece feature the Saint looking down at [[rat]]s that have gathered at his feet, often featuring 2-3 rats.<ref name=\"MartinHallSOS\"/>\n\n==Father Thomas McGlynn==\n\nMcGlynn was born May 23, 1906 to [[Frank McGlynn, Sr.|Frank McGlynn]] and Rose O'Beirne. On September 8, 1925 he received the habit of the [[Dominican Order]], taking the name Brother Matthew. At Dominic's Church in Washington, D.C., he was [[ordained]] a priest on May 20, 1932 by [[Michael Joseph Curley|Archbishop Michael Joseph Curley]]. Receiving his degree in sculpture in [[Rome, Italy]] in 1934 and returned to the United States to study at [[Cranbrook Educational Community]] studying under [[Carl Milles]]. After apostolic ministry and serving as faculty member at Providence College (1937\u20131938 and 1946), he went to [[Pietrasanta, Italy]] in 1956 commissioned to create a sculpture of [[Our Lady of Fatima]] and he remained in the country until his death on September 3, 1977.<ref name=\"MartinHallSOS\">{{cite web | author=Smithsonian | year=1993 | title=Saint Martin de Porres, (sculpture). | work=Save Outdoor Sculpture | publisher=Smithsonian | url=http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?&profile=all&source=~!siartinventories&uri=full=3100001~!319555~!0#focus | accessdate= 12 January 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"McGlynn\">{{cite web | author=Fr. Richard McAlister OP | title=Dominican Priest and Sculptor Thomas McGlynn | work=Theology | publisher=Providence College | url=http://www.domcentral.org/library/McGlynn/default.htm | accessdate=12 January 2010 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100501091551/http://www.domcentral.org/library/McGlynn/default.htm | archivedate=1 May 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==Inspiration and Creation==\n\nGrowing up, McGlynn was unaware of racial issues during his youth, using discriminatory terms as part of everyday life to describe [[African Americans]]. Upon entering the priesthood McGlynn states that \"My meeting with Martin de Porres changed all that.\"<ref name=\"Homily\">{{cite web | author=Fr. Pius Pietrzyk, O.P. | year=2010 | title=Fr. Thomas McGlynn and St. Martin de Porres | work=Friar Blog | publisher=The Dominican Province of Saint Joseph | url=http://www.op-stjoseph.org/blog/fr._thomas_mcglynn_and_st._martin_de_porres/ | accessdate= 12 January 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Locations==\nFour versions of the sculpture exist, and the creation of this work is often credited with contributing to the [[canonization]] of the Saint in 1962.<ref name=\"2009McGlynn\">{{cite web | year=2009 | title=Selected Works of Thomas McGlynn | work=Thomas McGlynn | publisher=Providence College | url=http://www.domcentral.org/library/McGlynn/mcg09.htm | accessdate=12 January 2010 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101229191514/http://www.domcentral.org/library/McGlynn/mcg09.htm | archivedate=29 December 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==Dominican House of Studies==\n\nThe original [[plaster]] version of the sculpture resided in the collection of the Dominican House of Studies in Washington, D.C. as of 1962.<ref name=\"2009McGlynn\"/>\n\n===Vatican===\n\nThe first, small version of the sculpture was created for use at the Vatican, completed in 1962.<ref name=\"2009McGlynn\"/>\n\n===Providence College===\n\nProvidence College has two copies of the sculpture, one in front of Martin Hall and a second at the McGlynn Sculpture Court, named after the sculptor. The Martin Hall sculpture, the fourth in the series, has no rats at the Saints feet, is made of [[bronze]] (H. 7&nbsp;ft.) and was copyrighted in 1958 and dedicated on November 3, 1979.<ref name=\"MartinHallSOS\"/> This version was originally designed for [[Saint Raymond's Cemetery, Bronx|Saint Raymond's Cemetery]] in the Bronx, New York City, and McGlynn decided to remove the rats believing that people would have an aversion to them being on a sculpture in a cemetery.<ref name=\"2009McGlynn\"/> It was surveyed in 1993 by the [[Smithsonian Institution|Smithsonian's]] [[Save Outdoor Sculpture!]] program and was described as needing treatment.<ref name=\"MartinHallSOS\"/>  \n\nThe second sculpture, at McGlynn Sculpture Court, features several small rats at the Saints feet. This is an earlier version of the above piece, made also of bronze (H. 48 in. \u00d7 W. 1&nbsp;ft. 3 in.), created in 1962, cast in 1963 and dedicated on October 2, 1993. The sculpture stands in a small fountain. as part of the Sculpture Court which was built after the [[Dominican Province of St. Joseph]] donated their McGlynn Archives & Sculpture Collection to the College in 1980. This sculpture was described as well maintained by the Save Outdoor Sculpture! survey program.<ref name=\"SOS1993\"/>\n\n==Our Lady of Perpetual Help Church==\n\nThis version of the sculpture is made of [[wood]] (H. 12{{frac|1|2}} ft.) and does not feature the rats at his feet. It was dedicated on May 27, 1989 with the support of the St. Martin de Porres Guild and the founding pastor who wanted the church to be dedicated in the Saints honor. The funds for the work were provided by an endowment supplied by parishioner Mary A. Cooke, who hoped to have the statue erected inside the church school. The piece resides outside. The work was described as needing treatment in 1994 by the Save Outdoor Sculpture! survey program.<ref name=\"SOS1994\"/>\n\n===Roman Catholic Diocese of Raleigh===\n\nOn November 3, 2009, the parish of St. Joseph in [[Raleigh, North Carolina]] was presented a four-foot-tall version of the sculpture by Fr. Ambrose McAlister, Professor Emeritus of Art and Art History at Providence College, to celebrate the Feast of St. Martin de Porres.<ref name=\"Homily\"/> This black marble casting was made from the 1930 version and was created in a Rhode Island-based foundry. It sits upon a table of white [[carrara marble]], which was crafted by parish member Bill Stephany. Fundraising for the work and installation was spearheaded by parish member Daisy Foster. Father McGlynn worked in Raleigh at St. Monica's from 1947 to 1954.<ref name=\"Raleigh\">{{cite web | author=St. Martin de Porres | year= | title=St. Martin de Porres | work= | publisher=St. Joseph's Catholic Church | url=http://stjosephsraleigh.org/index.php?option=com_content&id=92 | accessdate= 12 January 2010}}</ref>\n\n===St. Martin de Porres Shrine & Institute, Memphis, Tennessee===\n\nThe shrine chapel features a small version of the 1930 casting which shares the space with a [[relic]] of St. Martin as well as a stained-glass window and icons created by [[Pam Hassler]].<ref name=\"Shrine\">{{cite web | year=2010 | title=Shrine Artwork | work=The Shrine Chapel | publisher=St. Martin de Porres Shrine & Institute | url=http://www.stmartinshrine.org/shrinechapel.html | accessdate=12 January 2010 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100826074913/http://www.stmartinshrine.org/shrinechapel.html | archivedate=26 August 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20101229190116/http://www.domcentral.org/library/McGlynn/mcg03.htm Learn more about Father McGlynn]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saint Martin De Porres (Sculpture)}}\n[[Category:Providence College]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials in Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:Culture of Providence, Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Outdoor sculptures in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Sculptures of saints]]\n[[Category:Woodcarving]]\n[[Category:Catholic Church in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:African-American Roman Catholicism]]\n[[Category:1963 sculptures]]\n[[Category:Bronze sculptures in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Ham II", "label": "safe", "comment": "+Template:Public art in 