} (original span)\n| toll          = Cars (eastbound only)<br />$6.00 (cash or [[FasTrak]]), $3.00 <ref>https://www.bayareafastrak.org/en/howitworks/whereToUse.shtml#carquinez</ref>(carpools during peak hours, FasTrak only)\n| map_type      = United States San Francisco Bay Area#California#United States\n| map_image     =\n| map_text      =\n| map_width     =\n| coordinates   = {{Coord|38.0608|N|122.2257|W|region:US_type:landmark|display=inline,title|format=dms}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Carquinez Bridge''' is a pair of [[parallel (geometry)|parallel]] bridges spanning the [[Carquinez Strait]] at the northeastern end of [[San Francisco Bay]]. They form the part of [[Interstate 80 in California|Interstate 80]] between [[Crockett, California|Crockett]] and [[Vallejo, California|Vallejo]], [[California]]. The name Carquinez Bridge originally referred to a single [[cantilever bridge]] built in 1927, which was part of the direct route between [[San Francisco]] and [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]]. A second parallel cantilever bridge was completed in 1958 to deal with the increased traffic. Later, seismic problems made the 1927 span unsafe in case of an earthquake, and led to the construction, and 2003 opening, of a replacement: a [[suspension bridge]] officially named the '''Alfred Zampa Memorial Bridge''', in memory of iron worker [[Al Zampa]], who played an integral role in the construction of numerous [[San Francisco Bay Area]] bridges. The Alfred Zampa Memorial Bridge carries westbound traffic from Vallejo to Crockett, and the 1958 cantilever span carries eastbound traffic.\n\n==History and description==\nThe first regular crossing of the Carquinez Strait began in the mid-1800s as a ferry operated between the cities of Benicia and Martinez, six miles upstream from the bridge site. Auto service started on this route in 1913. A [[train]] ferry operated between Benicia and Porta Costa from 1879 until 1930 when a rail bridge opened. Ferry service at the site of the bridge started in 1913 by the Rodeo-Vallejo Ferry Company.<ref>Hope, Andrew (2000). [http://loc.gov/pictures/item/ca3089/ Carquinez Bridge, Spanning Carquinez Strait at Interstate 80, Vallejo, Solano County, CA], Historic American Engineering Record. p. 11.</ref>\n\n===Original span (1927\u20132007)=== \nThe original steel [[cantilever bridge]] was designed by [[David B. Steinman|Robinson & Steinman]] and dedicated on May 21, 1927. Prior to this, crossing the [[Carquinez Strait]] necessitated the use of [[Six Minute ferries|ferries]]. The bridge cost $8 million to build. It was the first major crossing of the [[San Francisco Bay]]<ref>''The Barrier Broken'' \u2013 Vallejo Evening Chronicle, May 21, 1927</ref> and a significant technological achievement in its time.\n\nUpon its completion, the span became part of the [[Lincoln Highway]]. This historic transcontinental roadway's original alignment, like the [[First Transcontinental Railroad|Transcontinental Railroad]] that preceded it nearly sixty years earlier, chose to avoid crossing the Carquinez Strait entirely. The preferred option, given the engineering limitations of the day, was to skirt around the [[Sacramento\u2013San Joaquin River Delta|Delta]] by going south from [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]] through [[Stockton, California|Stockton]], then proceeding west across the [[San Joaquin River]] and over the [[Altamont Pass]], and finally reaching [[Oakland, California|Oakland]] from the south; a route that would later become [[U.S. Route 50 in California|U.S. Route 50]] and ultimately Interstates [[Interstate 5 (California)|5]], [[Interstate 205 (California)|205]], and [[Interstate 580 (California)|580]]. This circuitous route, several miles longer, and traversing a rather formidable mountain pass, was preferable to crossing the Carquinez Strait, a deep channel with strong currents and frequent high winds. For decades, building a bridge across the Carquinez Strait was considered prohibitively expensive and technologically risky. Once the bridge was built however, driving from Sacramento to the [[East Bay (San Francisco Bay Area)|East Bay]] became much more direct. The Carquinez Bridge provided a welcome alternative route from the [[Central Valley (California)|Central Valley]] to the [[San Francisco Bay Area|Bay Area]], one that no longer required loading one's vehicle onto and off of a ferry. With the bridge completed, the Lincoln Highway was realigned to cross the [[Sacramento River]], then proceed southwest through [[Davis, California|Davis]] and [[Vallejo, California|Vallejo]], across the Carquinez Bridge, and along the shores of the [[San Pablo Bay|San Pablo]] and [[San Francisco Bay|San Francisco]] bays to [[Richmond, California|Richmond]] and Oakland; becoming [[U.S. Route 40 in California|U.S. Route 40]], and ultimately [[Interstate 80 (California)|Interstate 80]].\n\nAfter the [[Loma Prieta earthquake]] engineers determined that the aging 1927 span was seismically unstable, and that a retrofit was impossible. The decision was made to replace it with a new suspension bridge. The 1927 span was  temporarily used to hold eastbound traffic while the 1958 eastbound span underwent a seismic retrofit, deck and superstructure rehabilitation, and painting to extend its serviceable life.<ref>[http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2006/04/25/MNG1IIENCQ1.DTL ''\"Old Carquinez Bridge is disappearing\"''] \u2013 San Francisco Chronicle, April 25, 2006.</ref>  The old 1923 cantelever bridge was dismantled three years after the opening of its replacement; with completion on September 4, 2007. A 3,000-pound bronze bell atop one of the bridge piers was removed and placed into storage. The bell will eventually be displayed in a new museum to be built at the Oakland end of the [[San Francisco\u2013Oakland Bay Bridge]].\n\n===Parallel span (1958)===\nAt a cost of $38 million<ref name=\"bata.mtc.ca.gov\">{{cite web |url=http://bata.mtc.ca.gov/bridges/carquinez.htm |title=Bay Area Toll Authority \u2013 Bridge Facts \u2013 Carquinez Bridge |publisher=Bata.mtc.ca.gov |date=2011-01-27 |accessdate=2011-08-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110809141952/http://bata.mtc.ca.gov/bridges/carquinez.htm |archivedate=2011-08-09 }}</ref> a parallel bridge was built just east of the 1927 bridge. The new bridge carried all traffic for a few months after it opened in November 1958, then after new ramps were built the three-lane 1927 span, originally two-way, served westbound traffic while the four-lane 1958 span handled eastbound traffic.\n\n===Alfred Zampa Memorial Bridge (2003 replacement span)===\n[[Image:The Carquinez Bridge.jpg|thumb|left|Carquinez Bridge in 2006 with the 1927 span in the center.]]\n[[File:Carquinez Strait aerial view.jpg|thumb|Aerial view of Carquinez Strait and bridges, prior to construction of the new suspension bridge]]\n\nAt a cost of $240 million a new [[suspension bridge]] was built, to the west of the two earlier bridges, by the joint venture consisting of Flatiron Structures of Longmont, Co., FCI Constructors of Benicia, Ca., and the [[Cleveland Bridge & Engineering Company]] of Darlington, England.<ref name=\"bata.mtc.ca.gov\"/>\n\nThis new bridge was named the '''[[Al Zampa|Alfred Zampa]] Memorial Bridge''', after an ironworker who worked on a number of the San Francisco Bay Area bridges, including the [[Golden Gate Bridge]], and the original 1927 Carquinez span. The bridge was dedicated on November 8, 2003 and opened for traffic on November 11, 2003. Originally, the plan was to dedicate the bridge on November 15, but complications involving then just-recalled Governor [[Gray Davis]] and the transfer power to [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]] resulted in the date being moved. The coins minted to commemorate the event have the original date on them.<ref>[http://www.alzampabridge.com/index.htm \"Alfred Zampa memorial coins\"]{{Full citation needed|date=September 2009}} {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071007211620/http://www.alzampabridge.com/index.htm |date=October 7, 2007 }} \u2013 Official Web Site</ref>\n\nThe new suspension bridge, consists of the south anchorage, a transition pier, the South and North towers, and the north anchorage. It has spans of 147 m, 728 m, and 181 m. for a total span of {{convert|0.66|mi|m}}. It features a pedestrian and bicycle path, part of a bike trail which it is hoped will eventually [[San Francisco Bay Trail|circle the entire Bay Area]]. The towers are each founded on two footings, which are each supported by six vertical, {{convert|3|m|ft|adj=mid|-diameter}} steel shells infilled with reinforced concrete, followed by {{convert|2.7|m|ft|adj=mid|-diameter}} drilled shafts in rock, i.e., cast-in-drilled hole, or CIDH, piles. The total length of the CIDH pile at the South Tower is approximately 89 m, with about 43 m of drilled shaft in rock. The total length of the CIDH pile at the North Tower ranges from 49 to 64 m, with about 16 to 26 m of drilled shaft in rock. The design parameters used for the South Tower piles were later confirmed by a pile load test. Additional field investigations during construction revealed significant variations in rock conditions at the North Tower, resulting in the redesign of the length of the piles. Major construction challenges encountered during construction of the South Tower piles, and the revised construction procedure, i.e., under-reaming, used by the constructor to mitigate caving.\n\nMaterials for the New Bridge came from all over the world:\n\n* Steel Caissons for CIDH: XKT Engineering \u2013 Vallejo, California\n* Orthotropic Deck Sections: IHI \u2013 Japan\n* Tower and Splay Saddles: \n** Castings: Sheffield Steel \u2013 England\n** Finishing and Machining: Kvaerner \u2013 England\n* Main Cable Wire: [[Bridon Ropes|Bridon]] \u2013 England\n* Wire for Cable Wrapping: Canada\n* Cable Bands: France\n* Suspenders (Hardware, Casting, Fabrication): WRCA \u2013 St. Joseph, Missouri\n* (3) Maintenance Travelers Under Deck Sections: Jesse Engineering \u2013 Tacoma, Washington\n\n==Tolls==\nTolls are collected only from automotive traffic headed eastbound, towards Vallejo at the toll plaza on the north side of the bridge, which is unique in that the toll is collected after crossing the bridge. Although the 2003 Alfred Zampa Memorial Bridge is the newer span, no toll is charged in that direction, continuing the practice of when the now-demolished 1927 span. Since July 2010, the toll rate for passenger cars has been $5. During peak traffic hours, [[carpool]] vehicles carrying two or more people or motorcycles pay a discounted toll of $2.50.<ref>{{cite web |title=Frequently Asked Toll Questions |publisher=Bay Area Toll Authority |date=2010-06-01 |url=http://www.mtc.ca.gov/tolls/faq.htm#2 |accessdate=2010-06-29 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5tv1MQCqO?url=http://www.mtc.ca.gov/tolls/faq.htm#2 |archivedate=2010-11-01 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Toll Increase Information |publisher=Bay Area Toll Authority |date=2010-06-01 |url=http://www.mtc.ca.gov/tolls/ |accessdate=2010-06-29 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5tv15npOZ?url=http://www.mtc.ca.gov/tolls/ |archivedate=2010-11-01 |url-status=live }}</ref> For vehicles with more than two axles, the toll rate is $5 per axle.<ref>{{cite web|title=Toll Increase Information: Multi-Axle Vehicles |publisher=Bay Area Toll Authority |date=2012-07-01 |url=http://www.mtc.ca.gov/tolls/multi-axle.htm |accessdate=2013-12-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131230234900/http://www.mtc.ca.gov/tolls/multi-axle.htm |archivedate=2013-12-30 }}</ref> Drivers may either pay by cash or use the [[FasTrak]] electronic toll collection device.\n\n===Historical toll rates===\nCrossing the original 1927 bridge required a toll, but tolls were removed soon after the state bought the bridge in 1940. Tolls in 1926 were originally set at $0.60 per car plus $0.10 per passenger. This was reduced in 1938 to $0.45 per car plus $0.05 per passenger. After the state took ownership, tolls were immediately reduced to $0.30 per car. In 1942, tolls were further reduced to $0.25 before being removed in 1945. Tolls were reinstated in 1958 with the completion of the parallel span, set again at $0.25. It was increased to $0.35 in 1970, and then $0.40 in 1978.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.dot.ca.gov/dist4/documents/tollfees.pdf | title=History of California's Bridge Tolls | publisher=[[California Department of Transportation|Caltrans]] | accessdate=June 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe basic toll (for automobiles) on the seven state-owned bridges, including the Carquinez Bridge, was raised to $1 by Regional Measure 1, approved by Bay Area voters in 1988.<ref>[http://bata.mtc.ca.gov/projects/rm1.htm Regional Measure 1 Toll Bridge Program]. ''bata.mtc.ca.gov''; [[Bay Area Toll Authority]]. {{webarchive |url=https://www.webcitation.org/5tv15npOE?url=http://bata.mtc.ca.gov/projects/rm1.htm |date=November 1, 2010 }}</ref> A $1 seismic retrofit surcharge was added in 1998 by the state legislature, originally for eight years, but since then extended to December 2037 (AB1171, October 2001).<ref name='AB1171'>{{cite news|first=John |last=Dutra |title=AB 1171 Assembly Bill \u2013 Chaptered |date=October 14, 2001 |publisher=[[California State Assembly]] |url=http://www.leginfo.ca.gov/pub/01-02/bill/asm/ab_1151-1200/ab_1171_bill_20011014_chaptered.html |accessdate=August 7, 2008 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5tv15npOL?url=http://www.leginfo.ca.gov/pub/01-02/bill/asm/ab_1151-1200/ab_1171_bill_20011014_chaptered.html |archivedate=November 1, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> On March 2, 2004, voters approved Regional Measure 2, raising the toll by another dollar to a total of $3. An additional dollar was added to the toll starting January 1, 2007, to cover cost overruns concerning the replacement of the eastern span.\n\nThe [[Metropolitan Transportation Commission (San Francisco Bay Area)|Metropolitan Transportation Commission]], a regional transportation agency, in its capacity as the [[Bay Area Toll Authority]], administers RM1 and RM2 funds, a significant portion of which are allocated to public transit capital improvements and operating subsidies in the transportation corridors served by the bridges. Caltrans administers the \"second dollar\" seismic surcharge, and receives some of the MTC-administered funds to perform other maintenance work on the bridges. The Bay Area Toll Authority is made up of appointed officials put in place by various city and county governments, and is not subject to direct voter oversight.<ref>{{cite web|title=About MTC |publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Commission |date=October 15, 2009 |url=http://www.mtc.ca.gov/about_mtc/about.htm |accessdate=October 15, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5tv15npOg?url=http://www.mtc.ca.gov/about_mtc/about.htm |archivedate=November 1, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nDue to further funding shortages for seismic retrofit projects, the Bay Area Toll Authority again raised tolls on all seven of the state-owned bridges in July 2010. The toll rate for autos on the Carquinez Bridge was thus increased to $5.<ref>{{cite web |title=Frequently Asked Toll Questions |publisher=Bay Area Toll Authority |date=June 1, 2010 |url=http://www.mtc.ca.gov/tolls/faq.htm#2 |accessdate=June 29, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5tv1MQCqO?url=http://www.mtc.ca.gov/tolls/faq.htm#2 |archivedate=November 1, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn June 2018, Bay Area voters approved Regional Measure 3 to further raise the tolls on all seven of the state-owned bridges to fund $4.5 billion worth of transportation improvements in the area.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/3-hike-to-Bay-Area-tolls-appears-to-have-support-12972027.php | title=Regional Measure 3: Work on transportation improvements could start next year | first=Michael | last=Cabanatuan | publisher=SFGate.com | date=June 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.ktvu.com/news/bay-area-bridge-tolls-to-increase-one-dollar-in-january-except-golden-gate | title=Bay Area bridge tolls to increase one dollar in January, except Golden Gate | first=Christien | last=Kafton | publisher=KTVU | date=November 28, 2018}}</ref> Under the passed measure, the toll rate for autos on the Carquinez Bridge will be increased to $6 on January 1, 2019; to $7 on January 1, 2022; and then to $8 on January 1, 2025.<ref>{{cite press release | url=https://mtc.ca.gov/whats-happening/news/tolls-seven-bay-area-bridges-set-rise-next-month | title=Tolls on Seven Bay Area Bridges Set to Rise Next Month | publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Commission | date=December 11, 2018 | accessdate=December 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, the MTC approved a $4 million plan to eliminate toll takers and convert all seven of the state-owned bridges to [[all-electronic tolling]], citing that 80 percent of drivers are now using Fastrak and the change would improve traffic flow.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.sacbee.com/news/california/article234765937.html | title=Do you drive to the Bay Area? A big change is coming to toll booths at the bridges | first=Darrell | last=Smith | newspaper=The Sacramento Bee | date=September 7, 2019 | accessdate=April 12. 2020}}</ref> On March 20, 2020, at midnight, due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], all-electronic tolling was temporarily placed in effect for all seven state-owned toll bridges.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mtc.ca.gov/whats-happening/news/cash-toll-collection-suspended-bay-area-bridges|title=Cash Toll Collection Suspended at Bay Area Bridges|date=March 20, 2020|website=Metropolitan Transportation Commission|language=en|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Carquinez Bridge in the media==\n* The 1927 span of the Carquinez Bridge is featured on a Season 4 episode of [[MythBusters (2006 season)#Miniature Earthquake Machine|''MythBusters'']] in the Miniature Earthquake Machine segment. This experiment, based upon a claim by inventor [[Nikola Tesla]] that his [[Tesla's oscillator|mechanical oscillator]] produced an earthquake in 1898, employed a small tunable reciprocating mass driver to shake the bridge at its resonance frequency. While not structurally significant, the shaking was felt some distance from the driver.\n* An hour-length program, titled ''Break It Down: \"Bridge\"'', documenting the demolition of the 1927 bridge aired on [[National Geographic (U.S. TV Channel)|National Geographic Channel]], on November 1, 2007\n* On October 5, 2007, a man jumped off the new {{convert|156|ft|m|adj=mid|-high}} bridge. The [[United States Coast Guard|Coast Guard]], Vallejo Police, and Fire responded to find him on the breakwater. He survived the fall.\n* Four books have been published about, or featuring, the Carquinez Bridges:''Spanning the Carquinez Strait: The Alfred Zampa Memorial Bridge'' (2003) Cal-Trans, ''Spanning the Strait: Building the Alfred Zampa Memorial Bridge'' (2004) by John V. Robinson, and ''Al Zampa and the Bay Area Bridges'' (2005) by John V. Robinson and, most recently, ''Carquinez Bridge: 1927-2007'' (2017) by [[John V. Robinson]]\n{{Clear}}\n\n* The bridge was featured in the 2017 [[Netflix]] TV series [[13 Reasons Why]].\n\n==See also==\n* {{Portal-inline|Transport}}\n* {{Portal-inline|Engineering}}\n* {{Portal-inline|California}}\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n* [http://www.alzampabridge.com/ Alfred Zampa Memorial Bridge Foundation]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050629031336/http://www.lib.berkeley.edu/news_events/exhibits/bridge/ Bridging the Bay] History of the Carquinez Bridge, as well as other bridges.\n* [http://www.dot.ca.gov/dist4/carquinez.htm Caltrans New Carquinez Bridge page]\n* [http://www.ironmc.org/ Building the Al Zampa Bridge] \u2013 Site written by Dick McCabe Jr, a union ironworker who worked on the bridge with pictures of the construction and a journal of the construction progress.\n* [http://www.batolls.info/bridges/carquinez_bridge.html Live Toll Prices for Carquinez Bridge]\n* {{Structurae|id=20000482|title=Carquinez Strait Bridge (1927)}}\n* {{Structurae|id=20000483|title=Carquinez Strait Bridge (1958)}}\n* {{Structurae|id=20000913|title=Alfred Zampa Memorial (New Carquinez) Bridge (2003)}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071103080355/http://channel.nationalgeographic.com/channel/ET/popup/200711012100.html] Break it Down: \"Bridge\" on National Geographic Channel.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110809141952/http://bata.mtc.ca.gov/bridges/carquinez.htm] Bay Area Toll Authority Bridge Facts on Carquinez Bridge.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081120050717/http://www.carquinezpress.com/] Publisher's Web site for ''Spanning the Strait: Building the Alfred Zampa Memorial Bridge,'' John V. Robinson's book about the new bridge.\n* [http://www.opacengineers.com/features/Carquinez ''Third Carquinez Strait Bridge''] OAPC Consulting Engineers alternatives and selection report\n* {{HAER |id=ca3089 |survey=CA-297 |title=Carquinez Bridge, Spanning Carquinez Strait at Interstate 80, Vallejo, Solano County, CA |photos=126 |data=59 |cap=8}}\n\n{{San Francisco Bay watershed}}\n\n{{Crossings navbox\n|structure       = Crossings\n|place           = [[Carquinez Strait]]\n|bridge          = Carquinez Bridge\n|bridge signs    = [[Image:I-80 (CA).svg|20px|Interstate 80]]\n|upstream        = [[Benicia-Martinez Bridge]]\n|upstream signs  = [[Image:I-680 (CA).svg|24px|Interstate 680]]\n|downstream      = [[Richmond-San Rafael Bridge]]\n|downstream signs = [[Image:I-580 (CA).svg|24px|Interstate 580]]\n}}\n\n[[Category:Bridges in the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:Carquinez Strait]]\n[[Category:Bridges in Contra Costa County, California]]\n[[Category:Bridges in Solano County, California]]\n[[Category:Road bridges in California]]\n[[Category:Bridges on the Interstate Highway System]]\n[[Category:Interstate 80]]\n[[Category:Lincoln Highway]]\n[[Category:Steel bridges in the United States]]\n[[Category:Suspension bridges in California]]\n[[Category:San Francisco Bay]]\n[[Category:Toll bridges in California]]\n[[Category:Tolled sections of Interstate Highways]]\n[[Category:Vallejo, California]]\n[[Category:History of Solano County, California]]\n[[Category:Bridges completed in 1927]]\n[[Category:Bridges completed in 1958]]\n[[Category:Bridges completed in 2003]]\n[[Category:Historic American Engineering Record in California]]\n[[Category:San Francisco Bay Trail]]\n[[Category:Cantilever bridges in the United States]]\n[[Category:1927 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:U.S. Route 40]]\n", "name_user": "Keith D", "label": "safe", "comment": ". -> ,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carquinez_Bridge"}
{"title_page": "Convict Lake", "text_new": "{{Infobox body of water\n | name = Convict Lake\n | image = Convict Lake, Sierra Nevada Range, CA 9-16a (In Explore) (30501371946).jpg\n | caption = Convict Lake, with [[Laurel Mountain (California)|Laurel Mountain]] in the background\n | image_bathymetry = \n | caption_bathymetry = \n | location = [[Mono County, California|Mono County]], [[California]]\n | coords = {{coord|37.589|N|118.858|W|region:US-CA_type:waterbody|display=inline,title}}\n | type = \n | inflow =\n | outflow = \n | catchment = \n | basin_countries = United States\n | length  = {{Convert|0.9|mi|km|1|abbr=on}}\n | width   = {{Convert|0.4|mi|km|1|abbr=on}}\n | area = {{convert|170|acre}}\n | depth = \n | max-depth = {{convert|140|ft|m}}\n | volume = \n | residence_time = \n | shore = \n | elevation = {{Convert|7850|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}\n | islands = \n | cities = \n}}\n<!-- \n   ================================================================================================\n   *************   This article employs the 'No citations in the lede convention'   ***************\n   *************   i.e. All lede statements supported and cited in the text.        ***************\n   ================================================================================================\n-->\n'''Convict Lake''' is a [[lake]] located in [[Mono County, California]],  United States, situated in the [[Sherwin Range]] of the [[Sierra Nevada (U.S.)|Sierra Nevada]] mountains. It is known for its turquoise-blue water, the dramatic mountains (including [[Mount Morrison (California)|Mount Morrison]]) that surround it, the trout fishing it affords, and its unusual history. The lake, known to the Paiute as ''Wit-sa-nap'', was renamed by settlers after an incident on September 23, 1871, wherein a group of convicts escaped from prison in [[Carson City, Nevada]], and took refuge near the lake. They were pursued by a posse and after it caught up to the convicts a shootout followed, wherein a number of both posse members and convicts were killed or wounded. The remaining convicts who survived initially escaped but were eventually captured and lynched.\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Sevehah Cliff.jpg|thumb|Sevehah Cliff, composed of folded [[metamorphic rock]], provides a colorful backdrop to Convict Lake.]]\nConvict Lake was originally carved out by glaciers. The lake's surface is approximately {{convert|7850|ft|m}} above sea level, with its greatest depths approximately {{convert|140|ft|m}} deep in various places; it is among the deepest lakes in the Sierra Nevada mountains. The lake is oblong in shape and is surrounded by a [[Canyon#Box canyon|box canyon]] set in the mountains. [[Mount Morrison (California)|Mount Morrison]], the tallest mountain in the area at {{convert|12,241|ft|m}}, lies to the south-east of the lake.<ref name=mono>[[#tourism|Mono County Economic Development, Tourism and Film Commission, 2019]]</ref><ref name=gazett/><ref name=n'geo>[[#basin|National Geographic, Convict Creek Basin]]</ref>\n\nThe lake and canyon area is dominated by light colored [[granite]]. The [[sedimentary]] and [[metamorphic]] rocks in this area once overlaid the entire Sierra Nevada range but have now been eroded away, revealing the underlying granite that uplifted the range. During the formation of the Sierra Nevada mountain range, [[magma]] rose from great depths and obliterated much of the sedimentary rock with which it came in contact. Just below the surface, the magma cooled and formed the granite typical of the range. In the process extreme heat and pressure deformed the immediate overlying sedimentary rocks into numerous and striking shapes.<ref name=n'geo/>\n\n==History==\nThe [[Mono people|Paiute Indians]] of the region are said to have called Convict Lake ''Wit-sa-nap'':<ref>[[#visit|McKenna, 2019]], How Convict Lake Got its Name</ref> <blockquote>\"The streams which flowed from the mountains were supposed to be filled with ''Pot-sa-wa-gees'', water babies, who lived in spirit, but were visible to the eye, having the face of an Indian child and the body of a fish.\" \u2014 According to Indian legend, Hi-na-nu was a wise and noble man, whose spirit was reverenced by the Indians and to whom they looked for guidance in earthly matters.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://convictlake.com/our-resort/about/|title=About|website=Convict Lake Resort|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-23}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nConvict Lake, then known as Monte Diablo,<ref name=mono/> came to assume its present name in an unusual manner. On September 17, 1871, 29 prisoners, including murderers, horse thieves, train robbers, and other such convicts, escaped from the [[Nevada State Prison]] in Carson City, killing one guard and wounding several others.<ref name=\"gazett\">{{Cite web|url=http://desertgazette.com/blog/the-story-of-convict-lake/|title=The Story of Convict Lake {{!}} Desert Gazette|last=Feller|first=Walter|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-23}}</ref> The prisoners split into two groups, one of which was led by convicted murderer Charlie Jones. Jones previously had lived in Mono and Inyo counties and led his group south toward the [[Mammoth Lakes, California|Mammoth Lakes]] area. Needing food and supplies, the escaped convicts robbed several people as they went along their way. Crossing the [[Sierra Nevada (U.S.)|Sierra Nevada]] mountain range, Jones had hoped to reach the range's western slope, where they would be safe from pursuit. Jones correctly assumed that a Carson City [[Posse Comitatus (Common Law)|posse]] was on their trail, but the posse, from [[Benton, California]], led by [[Deputy Sheriff]] George Hightower, had given up within a couple of days and turned back. Meanwhile, on horseback, Billy Poor, a mail rider who was delivering mail for his first time, had accidentally encountered the group camped out near Convict Creek, a few miles south from the lake.<ref name=n'geo/> The convicts naturally assumed that the rider, if permitted to continue on, would reveal their location. Subsequently, Jones captured the man and, with the help of Leandor Morton, killed him,<ref name=tribune>[[#colorful|Tahoe Tribune, October 22, 2008]]</ref><ref>[[#inyo|Chalfant, 1922]], p. 215</ref><ref>[[#lakename|Convict Lake.com]]</ref> after which they took his horse and clothing and dressed his body in discarded prison cloths.<ref name=gazett/>\n\n[[File:Convictlake.jpg|thumb|Convict Lake lies in front of [[Mount Morrison (California)|Mount Morrison]].]]\nOutraged that, Poor, a Mono County resident, was murdered, the local community formed their own posse and pursued the convicts. By September 22, 1871, Sheriff George Hightower and Indian deputy Mono Jim led a new posse of 10 men and caught up to the convicts near Monte Diablo Creek. Early on the morning of September 23, Jones headed out for [[Bishop, California|Bishop]]. Wanting to break off from their group, Jones and another man told the others that they were going to look for food. The four remaining convicts were soon approached by the new posse, and a shootout occurred, leaving [[Wells Fargo Bank|Wells Fargo]] agent Morrison and Mono gunned down. The remaining convicts escaped to be captured later in Round Valley. By November 1, 18 of the 29 original prisoners had been captured. Jones and his partner had avoided the shootout but eventually were captured and executed.<ref>[[#down|U.S. Officer Down Memorial Page, Robert Morrison]]</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tahoedailytribune.com/sports/convict-lake-has-a-colorful-history/|title=Convict Lake has a colorful history|last=Evans|first=Jeremy|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-23}}</ref><ref>[[#resort|Convict Lake Resort, 2019]]</ref> The remaining convicts were either killed in the shootout, or captured and lynched on the trip back to the prison.<ref name=n'geo/> Mount Morrison, the highest peak in the area, was named after the slain Robert Morrison, with its nearby smaller peak named after Mono Jim.<ref name=tribune/>\n\n===1990 drownings===\n[[File:Convict Lake & Mt Morrison, 2019b.jpg|thumb|Convict Lake in late June, with its characteristic turquoise-blue color. The snow and ice is still present around the mountain top and melting into a stream that feeds the lake near the base of the mountain.]]\nIn February 1990, Convict Lake was the site of a major drowning. Twelve teenagers and two counselors from nearby Camp O'Neal, an institution for juvenile delinquents located near [[Whitmore Hot Springs, California]],<ref name=mamtimes>[[#book|Mammoth Times, February 17, 2012]]</ref> were there on a holiday outing.  At least four teenagers and both adults fell through the thin ice and into the water.  By the time the first rescuer arrived on the scene, only one teenager had been able to pull himself out of the water, but the other teenagers were no longer in sight, having apparently already drowned.<ref>[[#thinice|Los Angeles Times, February 21, 1990]]</ref>\n\nIn all, three teenagers from the camp and four would-be rescuers drowned in the freezing water. Another youth and a volunteer fire chief were rescued. Shortly before their deaths, the youths had been advised that the ice was too thin to support their weight but failed to heed the warning.<ref>[[#heed|Los Angeles Times, February 20, 1990]]</ref>\n\nAs a result of the drownings, Camp O'Neal was investigated and subsequently shut down due to findings of abuse and neglect.<ref name=mamtimes/>\n\n==Recreation==\n[[File:Bachforelle Zeichnung.jpg|upright=1.1|thumb|Brown trout common to Convict Lake]]\nConvict Lake is known for its fishing, including [[rainbow trout]], German [[brown trout]], and a species of sucker fish. Due to the high demand of fishing in the lake and stream, the lake is stocked once a week during the summer with rainbow trout, supplied by nearby hatcheries.<ref>[[#crest|Malloy, 2019: Convict Lake]]</ref> The biggest fish caught in Convict Lake was a {{convert|19+1/2|lb|adj=on}} [[Brown trout|German brown]], in 1956. More recently, a {{convert|14+1/2|lb|adj=on}} brown trout was caught on October 17, 1993, which also was the biggest trout caught in the Eastern Sierra that year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1994-05-11-sp-56311-story.html|title=Spreading the Noose : Convict Lake, Site of a Shootout Between Prison Escapees and a Posse in 1871, a Popular Paradise for Sierra Anglers|date=1994-05-11|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-23}}</ref>\n\nA {{convert|3|mi|0|adj=on}} trail for hiking goes around the lake. Another trail connects the lake to the [[Sierra Crest]].<ref>[[#loop|Convict Lake Resort, 2019]]</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n[[File:Convict Lake Pano.jpg|thumb|upright=1.1|Convict Lake, wide view looking west from the east end of the lake]]\n*The Western film ''[[The Secret of Convict Lake]]'' (1951) was largely based on the events that occurred at the lake in 1871.<ref>[[#tcm|Turner Classic Movies, Inc., 2010]]</ref> \n*The Western movie ''[[Nevada Smith]]'' (1966) was filmed here.<ref name=schneider/>\n*The Western movie ''[[The Border Legion (1924 film)|The Border Legion]]'' (1924) was filmed here.<ref name=schneider>[[#schneider|Schneider, 2016]], p. 161</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of lakes in California]]\n* [[Mammoth Lakes, California]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|1}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{commons}}\n*{{cite web |title=How Convict Lake Got its Name |last=McKenna |first=Mike |year=2019 |url=https://www.visitmammoth.com/blogs/how-convict-lake-got-its-name |website=Visit Mammoth |accessdate=June 1, 2019 |ref=visit}}\n*{{cite web |title=Places to go |publisher=Mono County Economic Development, Tourism and Film Commission |url=https://www.monocounty.org/places-to-go/lakes-rivers-creeks/convict-lake/ |accessdate=July 1, 2019 |ref=tourism}}\n*{{cite web |title=Convict Creek Basin |publisher=National Geographic |url=https://www.sierranevadageotourism.org/content/convict-creek-basin/sieaf751a687577e68af  |accessdate=July 1, 2019 |ref=basin}}\n*{{cite web |title=Convict Lake has a colorful history |accessdate=July 1, 2019 |publisher=Tahoe Tribune |date=October 22, 2008 |url=https://www.tahoedailytribune.com/sports/convict-lake-has-a-colorful-history/ |ref=colorful}}\n*{{cite book|title=The Story of Inyo |publisher=The Author |first=WA |last=Chalfant |year=1922 |page=[https://archive.org/details/storyofinyo00chal/page/215 215] |url=https://archive.org/details/storyofinyo00chal |ref=inyo}}\n*{{cite web |title= History of the Convict Lake name  |accessdate=July 1, 2019 |url=https://convictlake.com/our-resort/about/ |website=ConvictLake.com |ref=lakename}}\n* {{cite web |title=Before Convict Lake was a Resort, It Was an Escape Route |authorlink= |publisher=Convict Lake Resort |year=2019 |accessdate=July 6, 2019 |url=https://convictlake.com/ |ref=resort }} \n* {{cite web |title=Convict Lake Loop |publisher=Convict Lake Resort |year=2010 |accessdate=July 6, 2019 |url=https://convictlake.com/activities/hiking-convict-lake/ |ref=loop }}\n*{{cite news|last1=Wilkinson|first1=Tracy|last2=Sappell|first2=Joel|title=Rescuers Worked Frantically as Victims Slipped Under Ice|newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=1990-02-21 |accessdate=2012-04-25|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1990-02-21/news/mn-984_1_thin-ice |ref=thinice}}\n*{{cite news|title=Book on Convict Lake drowning accident both heals, hurts|url=http://www.mammothtimes.com/content/book-convict-lake-drowning-accident-both-heals-hurts|newspaper=Mammoth Times|first=Wendilyn|last=Grasseschi|date=2012-02-17 |ref=book}}\n*{{cite news |url= http://articles.latimes.com/1990-02-20/news/mn-1121_1_holiday-skating-partyc.html|title=7 Apparently Drown in Freezing Sierra Lake : Tragedy: Witnesses describe futile efforts to save three teen-agers on a holiday skating party. Four other victims were trying to save them.|accessdate=2011-03-09 | work=Los Angeles Times |first1=Cathleen |last1=Decker| first2=Kendal|last2=Pate|date=1990-02-20 |ref=heed}}\n*{{cite book|author=Schneider, Jerry L. |date=2016|title=Western Filming Locations California Book 6|publisher= CP Entertainment Books |isbn=9780692722947 |ref=schneider}}\n*{{cite web |last=Malloy |first=Betsy |title=Convict Lake |year=2019 |publisher=TripSavvy / Dotdash publishing family |website=Tripsavvy.com |url=http://gocalifornia.about.com/od/casierraseast/a/convict_lake.htm |accessdate=July 2, 2019 |ref=crest}}\n*{{cite web |title=Posse Member Robert Morrison |publisher=United States Officer Down Memorial Page, Inc |accessdate=July 2, 2019 |url=https://www.odmp.org/officer/22633-posse-member-robert-morrison |ref=down}}\n* {{cite book |last= |first= |title=The Secret of Convict Lake |authorlink= |publisher=Turner Classic Movies, Inc. A Warner Media Company |year=2010 |accessdate=July 6, 2019 |url=http://www.tcm.turner.com/tcmdb/title/89433/The-Secret-of-Convict-Lake/ |ref=tcm}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://opentopomap.org/#map=14/37.58298/-118.85932 Topographical map of Lake Convict and surrounding area]\n\n\n[[Category:Lakes of the Sierra Nevada (U.S.)]]\n[[Category:Lakes of Mono County, California]]\n[[Category:Inyo National Forest]]\n[[Category:Lakes of California]]\n[[Category:Lakes of Northern California]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox body of water\n | name = Convict Lake\n | image = Convict Lake, Sierra Nevada Range, CA 9-16a (In Explore) (30501371946).jpg\n | caption = Convict Lake, with [[Laurel Mountain (California)|Laurel Mountain]] in the background\n | image_bathymetry = \n | caption_bathymetry = \n | location = [[Mono County, California|Mono County]], [[California]]\n | coords = {{coord|37.589|N|118.858|W|region:US-CA_type:waterbody|display=inline,title}}\n | type = \n | inflow =\n | outflow = \n | catchment = \n | basin_countries = United States\n | length  = {{Convert|0.9|mi|km|1|abbr=on}}\n | width   = {{Convert|0.4|mi|km|1|abbr=on}}\n | area = {{convert|170|acre}}\n | depth = \n | max-depth = {{convert|140|ft|m}}\n | volume = \n | residence_time = \n | shore = \n | elevation = {{Convert|7850|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}\n | islands = \n | cities = \n}}\n<!-- \n   ================================================================================================\n   *************   This article employs the 'No citations in the lede convention'   ***************\n   *************   i.e. All lede statements supported and cited in the text.        ***************\n   ================================================================================================\n-->\n'''Convict Lake''' is a [[lake]] located in [[Mono County, California]],  United States, situated in the [[Sherwin Range]] of the [[Sierra Nevada (U.S.)|Sierra Nevada]] mountains. It is known for its turquoise-blue water, the dramatic mountains (including [[Mount Morrison (California)|Mount Morrison]]) that surround it, the trout fishing it affords, and its unusual history. The lake, known to the Paiute as ''Wit-sa-nap'', was renamed by settlers after an incident on September 23, 1871, wherein a group of convicts escaped from prison in [[Carson City, Nevada]], and took refuge near the lake. They were pursued by a posse and after it caught up to the convicts a shootout followed, wherein a number of both posse members and convicts were killed or wounded. The remaining convicts who survived initially escaped but were eventually captured and lynched.\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Sevehah Cliff.jpg|thumb|Sevehah Cliff, composed of folded [[metamorphic rock]], provides a colorful backdrop to Convict Lake.]]\nConvict Lake was originally carved out by glaciers. The lake's surface is approximately {{convert|7850|ft|m}} above sea level, with its greatest depths approximately {{convert|140|ft|m}} deep in various places; it is among the deepest lakes in the Sierra Nevada mountains. The lake is oblong in shape and is surrounded by a [[Canyon#Box canyon|box canyon]] set in the mountains. [[Mount Morrison (California)|Mount Morrison]], the tallest mountain in the area at {{convert|12,241|ft|m}}, lies to the south-east of the lake.<ref name=mono>[[#tourism|Mono County Economic Development, Tourism and Film Commission, 2019]]</ref><ref name=gazett/><ref name=n'geo>[[#basin|National Geographic, Convict Creek Basin]]</ref>\n\nThe lake and canyon area is dominated by light colored [[granite]]. The [[sedimentary]] and [[metamorphic]] rocks in this area once overlaid the entire Sierra Nevada range but have now been eroded away, revealing the underlying granite that uplifted the range. During the formation of the Sierra Nevada mountain range, [[magma]] rose from great depths and obliterated much of the sedimentary rock with which it came in contact. Just below the surface, the magma cooled and formed the granite typical of the range. In the process extreme heat and pressure deformed the immediate overlying sedimentary rocks into numerous and striking shapes.<ref name=n'geo/>\n\n==History==\nThe [[Mono people|Paiute Indians]] of the region are said to have called Convict Lake ''Wit-sa-nap'':<ref>[[#visit|McKenna, 2019]], How Convict Lake Got its Name</ref> <blockquote>\"The streams which flowed from the mountains were supposed to be filled with ''Pot-sa-wa-gees'', water babies, who lived in spirit, but were visible to the eye, having the face of an Indian child and the body of a fish.\" \u2014 According to Indian legend, Hi-na-nu was a wise and noble man, whose spirit was reverenced by the Indians and to whom they looked for guidance in earthly matters.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://convictlake.com/our-resort/about/|title=About|website=Convict Lake Resort|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-23}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nConvict Lake, then known as Monte Diablo,<ref name=mono/> came to assume its present name in an unusual manner. On September 17, 1871, 29 prisoners, including murderers, horse thieves, train robbers, and other such convicts, escaped from the [[Nevada State Prison]] in Carson City, killing one guard and wounding several others.<ref name=\"gazett\">{{Cite web|url=http://desertgazette.com/blog/the-story-of-convict-lake/|title=The Story of Convict Lake {{!}} Desert Gazette|last=Feller|first=Walter|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-23}}</ref> The prisoners split into two groups, one of which was led by convicted murderer Charlie Jones. Jones previously had lived in Mono and Inyo counties and led his group south toward the [[Mammoth Lakes, California|Mammoth Lakes]] area. Needing food and supplies, the escaped convicts robbed several people as they went along their way. Crossing the [[Sierra Nevada (U.S.)|Sierra Nevada]] mountain range, Jones had hoped to reach the range's western slope, where they would be safe from pursuit. Jones correctly assumed that a Carson City [[Posse Comitatus (Common Law)|posse]] was on their trail, but the posse, from [[Benton, California]], led by [[Deputy Sheriff]] George Hightower, had given up within a couple of days and turned back. Meanwhile, on horseback, Billy Poor, a mail rider who was delivering mail for his first time, had accidentally encountered the group camped out near Convict Creek, a few miles south from the lake.<ref name=n'geo/> The convicts naturally assumed that the rider, if permitted to continue on, would reveal their location. Subsequently, Jones captured the man and, with the help of Leandor Morton, killed him,<ref name=tribune>[[#colorful|Tahoe Tribune, October 22, 2008]]</ref><ref>[[#inyo|Chalfant, 1922]], p. 215</ref><ref>[[#lakename|Convict Lake.com]]</ref> after which they took his horse and clothing and dressed his body in discarded prison cloths.<ref name=gazett/>\n\n[[File:Convictlake.jpg|thumb|Convict Lake lies in front of [[Mount Morrison (California)|Mount Morrison]].]]\nOutraged that, Poor, a Mono County resident, was murdered, the local community formed their own posse and pursued the convicts. By September 22, 1871, Sheriff George Hightower and Indian deputy Mono Jim led a new posse of 10 men and caught up to the convicts near Monte Diablo Creek. Early on the morning of September 23, Jones headed out for [[Bishop, California|Bishop]]. Wanting to break off from their group, Jones and another man told the others that they were going to look for food. The four remaining convicts were soon approached by the new posse, and a shootout occurred, leaving [[Wells Fargo Bank|Wells Fargo]] agent Morrison and Mono gunned down. The remaining convicts escaped to be captured later in Round Valley. By November 1, 18 of the 29 original prisoners had been captured. Jones and his partner had avoided the shootout but eventually were captured and executed.<ref>[[#down|U.S. Officer Down Memorial Page, Robert Morrison]]</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tahoedailytribune.com/sports/convict-lake-has-a-colorful-history/|title=Convict Lake has a colorful history|last=Evans|first=Jeremy|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-23}}</ref><ref>[[#resort|Convict Lake Resort, 2019]]</ref> The remaining convicts were either killed in the shootout, or captured and lynched on the trip back to the prison.<ref name=n'geo/> Mount Morrison, the highest peak in the area, was named after the slain Robert Morrison, with its nearby smaller peak named after Mono Jim.<ref name=tribune/>\n\n===1990 drownings===\n[[File:Convict Lake & Mt Morrison, 2019b.jpg|thumb|Convict Lake in late June, with its characteristic turquoise-blue color. The snow and ice is still present around the mountain top and melting into a stream that feeds the lake near the base of the mountain.]]\nIn February 1990, Convict Lake was the site of a major drowning. Twelve teenagers and two counselors from nearby Camp O'Neal, an institution for juvenile delinquents located near [[Whitmore Hot Springs, California]],<ref name=mamtimes>[[#book|Mammoth Times, February 17, 2012]]</ref>, were there on a holiday outing.  At least four teenagers and both adults fell through the thin ice and into the water.  By the time the first rescuer arrived on the scene, only one teenager had been able to pull himself out of the water, but the other teenagers were no longer in sight, having apparently already drowned.<ref>[[#thinice|Los Angeles Times, February 21, 1990]]</ref>\n\nIn all, three teenagers from the camp and four would-be rescuers drowned in the freezing water. Another youth and a volunteer fire chief were rescued. Shortly before their deaths, the youths had been advised that the ice was too thin to support their weight but failed to heed the warning.<ref>[[#heed|Los Angeles Times, February 20, 1990]]</ref>\n\nAs a result of the drownings, Camp O'Neal was investigated and subsequently shut down due to findings of abuse and neglect.<ref name=mamtimes/>\n\n==Recreation==\n[[File:Bachforelle Zeichnung.jpg|upright=1.1|thumb|Brown trout common to Convict Lake]]\nConvict Lake is known for its fishing, including [[rainbow trout]], German [[brown trout]], and a species of sucker fish. Due to the high demand of fishing in the lake and stream, the lake is stocked once a week during the summer with rainbow trout, supplied by nearby hatcheries.<ref>[[#crest|Malloy, 2019: Convict Lake]]</ref> The biggest fish caught in Convict Lake was a {{convert|19+1/2|lb|adj=on}} [[Brown trout|German brown]], in 1956. More recently, a {{convert|14+1/2|lb|adj=on}} brown trout was caught on October 17, 1993, which also was the biggest trout caught in the Eastern Sierra that year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1994-05-11-sp-56311-story.html|title=Spreading the Noose : Convict Lake, Site of a Shootout Between Prison Escapees and a Posse in 1871, a Popular Paradise for Sierra Anglers|date=1994-05-11|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-23}}</ref>\n\nA {{convert|3|mi|0|adj=on}} trail for hiking goes around the lake. Another trail connects the lake to the [[Sierra Crest]].<ref>[[#loop|Convict Lake Resort, 2019]]</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n[[File:Convict Lake Pano.jpg|thumb|upright=1.1|Convict Lake, wide view looking west from the east end of the lake]]\n*The Western film ''[[The Secret of Convict Lake]]'' (1951) was largely based on the events that occurred at the lake in 1871.<ref>[[#tcm|Turner Classic Movies, Inc., 2010]]</ref> \n*The Western movie ''[[Nevada Smith]]'' (1966) was filmed here.<ref name=schneider/>\n*The Western movie ''[[The Border Legion (1924 film)|The Border Legion]]'' (1924) was filmed here.<ref name=schneider>[[#schneider|Schneider, 2016]], p. 161</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of lakes in California]]\n* [[Mammoth Lakes, California]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|1}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{commons}}\n*{{cite web |title=How Convict Lake Got its Name |last=McKenna |first=Mike |year=2019 |url=https://www.visitmammoth.com/blogs/how-convict-lake-got-its-name |website=Visit Mammoth |accessdate=June 1, 2019 |ref=visit}}\n*{{cite web |title=Places to go |publisher=Mono County Economic Development, Tourism and Film Commission |url=https://www.monocounty.org/places-to-go/lakes-rivers-creeks/convict-lake/ |accessdate=July 1, 2019 |ref=tourism}}\n*{{cite web |title=Convict Creek Basin |publisher=National Geographic |url=https://www.sierranevadageotourism.org/content/convict-creek-basin/sieaf751a687577e68af  |accessdate=July 1, 2019 |ref=basin}}\n*{{cite web |title=Convict Lake has a colorful history |accessdate=July 1, 2019 |publisher=Tahoe Tribune |date=October 22, 2008 |url=https://www.tahoedailytribune.com/sports/convict-lake-has-a-colorful-history/ |ref=colorful}}\n*{{cite book|title=The Story of Inyo |publisher=The Author |first=WA |last=Chalfant |year=1922 |page=[https://archive.org/details/storyofinyo00chal/page/215 215] |url=https://archive.org/details/storyofinyo00chal |ref=inyo}}\n*{{cite web |title= History of the Convict Lake name  |accessdate=July 1, 2019 |url=https://convictlake.com/our-resort/about/ |website=ConvictLake.com |ref=lakename}}\n* {{cite web |title=Before Convict Lake was a Resort, It Was an Escape Route |authorlink= |publisher=